'''Shinodajinja''' (しのだじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}{{ill|Hashimoto City|ja|橋本市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}{{ill|Takano-guchi Town|ja|高野口町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The {{ill|camphor tree|ja|クスノキ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the shrine grounds (the camphor tree of Shinodajinja) is a prefecturally designated {{ill|Natural Monument|ja|天然記念物|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

==概要==
This shrine is regarded as the guardian deity for the regions of Kuju, Uenaka, Tahara, and Shimonaka. Although its origins and history remain unknown, it is said that in {{ill|979|ja|979th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (the 2nd year of {{ill|Tengen (Japan)|ja|天元 (日本)|lt=Tengen|lt_ja=天元|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) the worship hall, offering hall, treasury, and tower gate were rebuilt. According to tradition, the enshrined deities were also said to have been {{ill|enshrined|ja|勧請|lt=Enshrinement|1=Kanjō|2=ja|3=分霊|4=es|5=Bunrei|6=id|7=Kanjō|8=zh|9=分靈|10=fr|11=Kanjō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} from the {{ill|Izumi Province|ja|和泉国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}’s {{ill|Seishinja (Izumi City)|ja|聖神社 (和泉市)|lt=Shinta no Mori|lt_ja=信太の森|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Locally, the shrine is known as the deity who seals away moles ({{ill|Mole|ja|モグラ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), with local lore claiming that moles have become extinct in the area. In {{ill|1909|ja|1909th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (February of the 42nd year of {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), it attained the status of a {{ill|Village Shrine|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

=== 境内 ===
* Main Hall (housing 5 shrines; wooden structure with a copper-plated roof; 1.62m<sup>2</sup>)<ref name="境内">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.wakayama-jinjacho.or.jp/jdb/sys/user/GetWjtTbl.php?JinjyaNo=4039 |title=信太神社 |access-date=2022-10-21 |publisher=和歌山県神社庁}}</ref>
* Shrine Office (wooden, tiled-roof, single-story structure; 25.9m<sup>2</sup>)<ref name="境内" />

==祭神==
* {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|lt=Amaterasu Imperial Deity|lt_ja=天照皇大神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (アマテラス)
* {{ill|Ninigi|ja|ニニギ|lt=Tenshin Hiko-Funahiko no Mikoto|lt_ja=天津彦火々瓊々杵尊|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (ニニギ)
* {{ill|Nigihayahi|ja|ニギハヤヒ|lt=Josasai Hiyori no Mikoto|lt_ja=饒早日尊|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (ニギハヤヒ)
* {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|lt=Kamiyawainarehiko no Mikoto|lt_ja=神倭磐禮彦尊|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Iwanagahime|ja|イワナガヒメ|1=Iwanaga-hime|lt=Iwanaga Hime|lt_ja=磐長比賣命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (イワナガヒメ)

==天然記念物==
[[File: Shinodajinjya Kusu.jpg|thumb|220px|信太神社の樟樹]]
According to late Edo Period local geography records such as the {{ill|Kii Continuation Fudoki|ja|紀伊続風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it is noted that "within the precincts there stands a great camphor tree (クス) surrounded by more than three jō in circumference, bearing witness to the ancient history of the shrine grounds." This camphor tree is a grand specimen with an approximate height of 25 {{ill|Meter|ja|メートル|lt=m|lt_ja=m|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and a trunk circumference of about 7 m. Estimated to be around 400 years old, the tree still boasts a luxuriant canopy with its vigor hardly diminished. At the base of its main trunk, a venerable specimen of {{ill|Kurogane Mochi|ja|クロガネモチ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with a trunk circumference of 2.1 m has become completely fused with the camphor tree’s root, forming a rare natural phenomenon.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url= http://www.city.hashimoto.lg.jp/guide/kyoikuiinkai/syougaku/bunka/bunnkazai/wakayamaken_siteibunkazai/omobun/1359698878625.html|publisher=橋本市|title=信太神社の樟樹|accessdate=2021-2-11}}</ref> On January 8, {{ill|1959|ja|1959th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (the 34th year of {{ill|Showa Period|ja|昭和|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), the camphor tree of Shinodajinja was designated a Natural Monument by the prefectural authorities.<ref>現地案内看板、橋本市教育委員会、平成5th year 3月設置</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.pref.wakayama.lg.jp/prefg/500700/mokuroku/kenkinenbutsu.html |title=県指定文化財・記念物（信太神社の樟樹）|access-date=2022-10-21 |publisher=和歌山県教育委員会}}</ref>

